=begin pod

=head1 08. The LLM Prompts Used

This chapter walks through the design process behind this tutorial — from a
first experiment that B<didn't> need a DSL, through consulting an LLM for
guidance, to the project spec that produced C<Slangify::Tutorial>.

=head2 First experiment: bill extraction

Starting point: a folder of utility bills.

=begin code
Ask Claude: "extract the data from these bills"
Result: bills.csv  ✓
=end code

It worked — but there was no need for a DSL. A plain LLM prompt handled the
extraction cleanly. The lesson: B<reach for a DSL only when structure and
validation matter downstream>.

This used approx. 10 bills, from the same utility provider. Possibly, the quality of data extraction would reduce with a more mixed bag of source material, more items or variations in LLM interpretation (eg different LLM models) which would suggest a return to the DSL strategy.

=head2 Consulting an LLM: where does DSL + LLM shine?

A conversation with ChatGPT surfaced the right use case:

I want an LLM to extract structured information from messy text — but without
hand-writing JSON schemas or fragile parsing logic.

Example input:

=begin code
Jane booked a table for 4 at 7:30pm tomorrow at Bistro Verde
=end code

Desired output:

=begin code :lang<json>
{
  "name": "Jane",
  "party_size": 4,
  "time": "7:30 PM",
  "restaurant": "Bistro Verde",
  "date": "tomorrow"
}
=end code

The DSL approach wins here because the output must be I<typed> and I<validated>
— not just text.

=head2 Project spec

Use C<mi6> to scaffold a new Raku project C<Slangify::Tutorial> in directory C<Slangify-Tutorial>.

Set out the specification via C<openspec>.

Make a DSL for this purpose using Raku Grammar and Actions (see examples at
L<https://slangify.org>). Declare any needed classes in the Actions file.

Make sure Grammar and Actions do the whole job so they can be used in the
L<Grammar Editor / Slangify Playground|https://play.slangify.org>.

Use C<JSON::Fast>, C<Actionable>, and C<LLM::Functions>. Prompt for other
Raku modules if needed.

Make a command C<Slangify-Tutorial> that takes the text as an argument and optionally
a filename for the JSON output.

=head2 Spec tweaks

=item Add docs and tests.
=item Use the standard Raku / IntelliJ C<.gitignore>.
=item Any class instantiated inside an Actions method (e.g. via C<.action($/)>)
SHALL be declared with a simple unqualified name (e.g. C<class Booking>)
rather than a fully-qualified namespace name (e.g. C<class Slangify::Tutorial::Booking>).
=item Make C<name> cover names with titles, first name, middle name, last name,
and so on.

